1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,680
Hi, this is a small little workflow tutorial for Rhino Spatial.

2
00:00:07,680 --> 00:00:14,720
Rhino Spatial is a grasshopper plugin for working with site context directly in Rhino.

3
00:00:14,720 --> 00:00:16,960
We're gonna start with the installation.

4
00:00:16,960 --> 00:00:24,160
The easiest way to install Rhino Spatial is via the package manager.

5
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:28,800
Make sure to include pre-releases when searching, because right now it's in alpha.

6
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:36,160
Let's search for Rhino Spatial and there it should be.

7
00:00:36,160 --> 00:00:37,600
Just click on install.

8
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:42,040
You also can install it via the component folder.

9
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:47,640
I did pre-load some data sets in this definition, but everything else I'm gonna do from scratch.

10
00:00:47,640 --> 00:00:52,800
The plugin is centered around the spatial context component.

11
00:00:52,800 --> 00:00:57,480
The basic idea behind it is we have a lot of data sets, we want to align to the same

12
00:00:57,560 --> 00:00:59,440
spatial coordinates.

13
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:04,640
The spatial context component has a few inputs, only one of the inputs is needed and that's

14
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:06,880
the open map.

15
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:10,680
We open it via a button.

16
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:15,900
Other inputs like use absolute coordinates or reference URL are not needed.

17
00:01:15,900 --> 00:01:22,520
By default the Rhino Spatial component loads everything near the zero zero point of Rhino,

18
00:01:23,040 --> 00:01:28,520
Rhino works best around the zero zero point, but you might want to use the absolute coordinates

19
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:32,200
and for that we have the Boolean toggle here.

20
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:34,520
Another helpful input is the reference URL.

21
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:41,840
For example I can choose this WFS layer here as a reference URL and then the map that's

22
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:49,720
gonna load is pre-loaded around the same area this data set is pre-loaded.

23
00:01:49,720 --> 00:01:54,240
So to select our area now we're just gonna click the button.

24
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:59,440
Then a browser window is going to open up and here you can see the pre-selected area

25
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:04,720
and we can select the area.

26
00:02:04,720 --> 00:02:14,120
I am going to select this area around the river.

27
00:02:14,120 --> 00:02:19,320
You can resize afterwards.

28
00:02:19,320 --> 00:02:23,080
Once you've selected the area you can just close the window.

29
00:02:23,080 --> 00:02:26,460
Now we have loaded the spatial context.

30
00:02:26,460 --> 00:02:35,240
If we now want to load the vector data here we're gonna need the load WFS component.

31
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:41,360
It can load a few different file types, some local, some URL.

32
00:02:41,360 --> 00:02:49,080
As I said you don't really need the reference URL so you can disconnect it right now.

33
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:57,440
Usually vector data sets have a few layers and for that we have the list layers component.

34
00:02:57,440 --> 00:03:03,960
In this case we want to list the vector layers which is the list WFS layers.

35
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:11,080
I know that there is just one layer in there which we can see if we add a panel you only

36
00:03:11,080 --> 00:03:13,580
see the one layer.

37
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:21,640
So we just can connect the layer and the WFS URL.

38
00:03:21,640 --> 00:03:26,720
The last thing we need is just the spatial context component.

39
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:33,920
And now it did load all the vector data around the area we selected.

40
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:37,940
Next I want to load in some WMS data.

41
00:03:37,940 --> 00:03:41,660
In our case here it's an aerial image.

42
00:03:41,660 --> 00:03:52,700
For that we need the load WMS component and a list WMS layers component.

43
00:03:52,700 --> 00:03:58,620
I know for a fact that this link has a few layers in there so we can look at them via

44
00:03:58,620 --> 00:04:01,100
the panel.

45
00:04:01,100 --> 00:04:06,800
We want to select layer 5 or rather layer 6 here.

46
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:16,600
We are going to do this via the list item component and a number slider.

47
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:18,700
We can now connect the layer.

48
00:04:18,700 --> 00:04:23,060
You can only ever load one WMS layer.

49
00:04:23,060 --> 00:04:29,100
For the vector layers you can load as many as you want via just one component.

50
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:33,340
Then we need to connect the URL.

51
00:04:33,340 --> 00:04:40,560
And of course the most important the spatial context component.

52
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:46,080
And there we have an aerial image aligned to the vector data.

53
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:48,600
Next I want to load some GeoTIFF files.

54
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:54,200
For that I am going to disable the aerial image here.

55
00:04:54,200 --> 00:05:00,280
The GeoTIFF component up here expects a local GeoTIFF file.

56
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:01,700
It's pretty easy.

57
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:07,000
Just connect the local file via a file path component.

58
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,220
And of course we need our spatial context again.

59
00:05:11,220 --> 00:05:13,020
And there we have it loaded in.

60
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:18,260
One thing of course is that it only loads georeferenced GeoTIFF files.

61
00:05:18,260 --> 00:05:25,260
If it can't read the EPSG data we can't really put it in the right spatial context.

62
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:28,100
Next I want to load some terrain data.

63
00:05:28,100 --> 00:05:31,340
For that we need the load terrain component.

64
00:05:31,340 --> 00:05:35,580
Load terrain of course needs the spatial context.

65
00:05:35,580 --> 00:05:38,380
The load terrain component has some fallback data.

66
00:05:38,380 --> 00:05:43,460
As you can see it's not that fine but it also accepts a few data sources.

67
00:05:43,460 --> 00:05:52,420
For example WCS URLs, local DEM files and a few more just basic point clouds.

68
00:05:52,420 --> 00:05:57,100
You can always read up in the github what it can load.

69
00:05:57,100 --> 00:06:02,340
And I did prepare this URL here which should be a bit better data.

70
00:06:02,340 --> 00:06:08,620
There we go.

71
00:06:08,620 --> 00:06:12,100
Next I want to load in some LOD2 data.

72
00:06:12,100 --> 00:06:14,220
There we have a few options again.

73
00:06:14,220 --> 00:06:18,060
We have the WFS or LOD links.

74
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:22,920
We can load in some CTGML or CTJSON data.

75
00:06:22,920 --> 00:06:27,920
In general most LOD2 data in an ACIP folder can be loaded in.

76
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:33,600
For loading in the LOD2 data we need the LOD2 component.

77
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:39,320
We need the source data.

78
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:44,320
We can select a layer here but we don't need to.

79
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:46,440
And of course we need the spatial context.

80
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:48,300
This might load a bit.

81
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:49,300
And there we have it.

82
00:06:49,300 --> 00:06:51,280
The LOD2 data is loaded in.

83
00:06:51,400 --> 00:06:55,180
It took a fairly long time to load in.

84
00:06:55,180 --> 00:06:58,080
And now we can work with it of course.

85
00:06:58,080 --> 00:07:06,520
For example we can bake it.

86
00:07:06,520 --> 00:07:09,400
Next is something a bit different.

87
00:07:09,400 --> 00:07:15,040
We gonna load in some OpenStreetMap data via the LoadOSM component.

88
00:07:15,040 --> 00:07:20,440
The OSM component loads in OpenStreetMap data via the Overpass API.

89
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:25,680
So the only thing you really need is the spatial context component.

90
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:33,520
Also you need to select what things you wanna load in via a boolean toggle.

91
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:43,880
I wanna load in all the data so I'm gonna select true and just select all of the things.

92
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:52,760
And now we just need to connect the spatial context component.

93
00:07:52,760 --> 00:07:55,760
Here again this might load a fairly long time.

94
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:58,960
Ok that took a long time but now it's loaded in.

95
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:04,640
I'm gonna hide the LOD2 data for a second here.

96
00:08:04,640 --> 00:08:08,400
By the way by default buildings are always loaded in.

97
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:11,240
You just need to select the other ones.

98
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:19,480
I'm gonna display it a bit better.

99
00:08:19,480 --> 00:08:21,720
And there we have it displayed a bit better.

100
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:28,000
Now one thing you see here is that the spatial context component aligns everything or rather

101
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:31,160
every 3D element in 3D space.

102
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:38,520
So the LOD2 data usually sits at the same height as the OSM data.

103
00:08:38,520 --> 00:08:46,100
But all the 2D data which includes in this case the greenery or water is displayed in

104
00:08:46,100 --> 00:08:47,280
one plane.

105
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:54,920
So if we load in the terrain data we should see that the OSM buildings are aligned to

106
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:58,840
the terrain fairly well.

107
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:01,080
And yeah we can see it here.

108
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:07,060
Oh and the buildings not looking right here are just mesh rendering alias.

109
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:17,220
So if you bake the buildings they should be displayed right because the data is right.

110
00:09:17,220 --> 00:09:20,100
It's just a display failure here.

111
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:22,740
I think the mesh count is too low.

112
00:09:22,740 --> 00:09:26,820
And now as a bit of a bonus here is the last component.

113
00:09:26,820 --> 00:09:29,900
It's the Google 3D tiles component.

114
00:09:29,900 --> 00:09:34,140
It's under a new tab because it's under the view tab.

115
00:09:34,220 --> 00:09:40,460
It doesn't allow you to actually download the data you just can display the data.

116
00:09:40,460 --> 00:09:43,260
And that's what we are doing here.

117
00:09:43,260 --> 00:09:53,060
We are basically aligning a Google Maps or Google Earth rather image to our spatial context.

118
00:09:53,060 --> 00:09:59,340
What we need for that is a Google API key or rather a Maps tiles API key.

119
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:03,740
As I said you only can use the data for display purposes.

120
00:10:03,740 --> 00:10:08,020
So Google doesn't allow you to save it.

121
00:10:08,020 --> 00:10:11,300
I've loaded my API key in here.

122
00:10:11,300 --> 00:10:17,180
We of course want it in the same spatial context so we are going to load the spatial context.

123
00:10:17,180 --> 00:10:22,020
By default it is disabled because it takes a fairly long time to load.

124
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:25,340
To enable it you just need a boolean toggle again.

125
00:10:25,340 --> 00:10:35,940
There it is loaded in.

126
00:10:35,940 --> 00:10:38,340
As you can see it is a bit buggy.

127
00:10:38,340 --> 00:10:42,620
Sometimes you need to reselect the spatial context because right now it only loads half.

128
00:10:42,620 --> 00:10:46,460
I clearly need to work a bit more on it.

129
00:10:46,460 --> 00:10:49,940
Let me turn off the preview here.

130
00:10:49,940 --> 00:10:55,220
You can see it's not a lot selected here.

131
00:10:55,220 --> 00:11:02,460
You can try to rerun it or usually it just helps to reselect the area.

132
00:11:02,460 --> 00:11:05,580
And by the way baking doesn't really work.

133
00:11:05,580 --> 00:11:10,060
You can click on it but it doesn't bake anything.

134
00:11:10,060 --> 00:11:15,260
Because as I've mentioned you are not really allowed to save the data.

135
00:11:15,260 --> 00:11:20,080
You can only display it and look at it in the context in this case.

136
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:25,480
You might want to see if something you have modeled is aligned to it or rather what it

137
00:11:25,480 --> 00:11:29,080
would look like behind the things you have modeled.

138
00:11:29,080 --> 00:11:32,280
And that's basically all the functionality.

